  "text": "During respiration, mitochondria produce ATP and ROS; within mitochondria the O 2 -Á is the immediate product of multiple enzymes, including the enzymes and other components (e.g., iron-sulfur clusters, quinones and cytochromes) of mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation. It seems that O 2 -Á is mainly generated at complexes I and III of the electron transport chain (ETC). Apart from the ETC, there are other sources of ROS in mitochondria, for example, enzyme systems such as 2-oxoglutarate, pyruvate dehydrogenase, and flavoprotein acyl-CoA dehydrogenase [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . While superoxide is continuously produced by respiring mitochondria, H 2 O 2 is rapidly generated due to spontaneous and enzymatic O 2 -Á dismutation by Mn-SOD. Moreover, H 2 O 2 can be directly formed by the action of p66Shc and monoamine oxidases. H 2 O 2 can affect cell function by reacting with thiol residues in redox-sensitive proteins in either the mitochondria or cytoplasm. In fact, while H 2 O 2 easily crosses the biological membranes, the negatively charged O 2 -Á does not permeate the lipid bilayer of membranes. However, we should keep in mind that O 2 -Á is able to pass through the pore of anion channels (AC), such as voltage-dependent mitochondrial anion channel (Fig. 6) .",
